    [State createStateWithName:@"Puerto Rico" population:3615086 statenickname:@"Isla del Encanto" history:@"The ancient history of the archipelago known today as Puerto Rico is not well known. Unlike other larger, more advanced indigenous communities in the New World (Aztec and Inca) whose people left behind abundant archeological and physical evidence of their societies, the indigenous population of Puerto Rico left scant artifacts and evidence.Between the 7th and 11th centuries, the Taíno culture developed on the island; by approximately 1000 AD, it had become dominant.\nWhen Columbus arrived in Puerto Rico during his second voyage on November 19, 1493, the island was inhabited by the Taíno. They called it Borikén.  Columbus named the island San Juan Bautista, in honor of the Catholic saint, John the Baptist. Eventually, traders and other maritime visitors came to refer to the entire island as Puerto Rico, and San Juan became the name of the main trading/shipping port.\nOn July 25, 1898, during the Spanish–American War, the U.S. invaded Puerto Rico with a landing at Guánica. As an outcome of the war, Spain ceded Puerto Rico, along with the Philippines and Guam, then under Spanish sovereignty, to the U.S. under the Treaty of Paris.  The United States and Puerto Rico began a long-standing metropolis-colony relationship.  In 1914, the Puerto Rican House of Delegates voted unanimously in favor of independence from the United States, but this was rejected by the U.S. Congress as \"unconstitutional,\" and in violation of the 1900 Foraker Act.\nNatural disasters, including a major earthquake and tsunami in 1918, and several hurricanes, and the Great Depression impoverished the island during the first few decades under U.S. rule.During the 1950s, Puerto Rico experienced rapid industrialization, due in large part to Operación Manos a la Obra (\"Operation Bootstrap\"), an offshoot of FDR's New Deal, which aimed to transform Puerto Rico's economy from agriculture-based to manufacturing-based. Presently, Puerto Rico has become a major tourist destination, as well as a global center for pharmaceutical manufacturing - yet it still struggles to define its political status." since:NSNotFound governor:@"Alejandro Padilla" sports:@"n/a" crime:@"n/a" themepark:@"Cayo Lobos Marine Park, Cayo Lobos\nChildren's Dream Park, Añasco\nFun Valley Park, Arecibo\nJungle Park PR, Bayamón\nParque de las Ciencias, Bayamón\nVilla Campestre, Guynado\nWonderPark, Carolina" abbreviation:@"PR" museums:@"Museo de Arte de Puerto Rico (San Juan)\nMuseo de Arte de Ponce (Ponce)" shoppingcenters:@"" touristattractions:@"	Mayagüez Mall (Mayagüez)\nPlaza Carolina (Carolina)\nPlaza del Norte (Hatillo)\nPlaza del Sol (Bayamón)\nPlaza Las Américas (San Juan)\nSanta Rosa Mall (Bayamón)" managedObjectContext:context];
    
    [State createStateWithName:@"Rhode Island" population:1051511 statenickname:@"Ocean State" history:@"In 1636, Roger Williams, after being banished from the Massachusetts Bay Colony for his religious views, settled at the tip of Narragansett Bay, on land granted to him by the Narragansett and Pequot tribes. Both tribes were subservient to the Wampanoag tribe led by Massasoit. He called the site Providence \"having a sense of God's merciful providence unto me in my distress.\"\nIn 1638, after conferring with Williams, Anne Hutchinson, William Coddington, John Clarke, Philip Sherman, and other religious dissidents settled on Aquidneck Island (then known as Rhode Island), which was purchased from the local natives, who called it Pocasset. Rhode Island was heavily involved in the slave trade during the post-revolution era. In 1774, the slave population of Rhode Island was 6.3%, nearly twice as high as any other New England colony. In the years after the Revolution, Rhode Island merchants controlled between 60% and 90% of the American trade of African slaves.\nIn addition to the slave trade, Rhode Island was also heavily involved in the Industrial Revolution. The Industrial Revolution began in America in 1787 when Thomas Somers reproduced textile machine plans he imported from England. He helped to produce the Beverly Cotton Manufactory, which Moses Brown of Providence took an interest in. Teaming up with Samuel Slater, Moses Brown helped to create the second cotton mill in America, a water-powered textile mill. As the Industrial Revolution moved large numbers of workers into the cities, a permanently landless, and therefore voteless, class developed.\nSince the Great Depression, the Rhode Island Democratic Party has dominated local politics. Rhode Island has comprehensive health insurance for low-income children, and a large social safety net. Many urban areas still have a high rate of children in poverty. Due to an influx of residents from Boston, increasing housing costs have resulted in more homeless in Rhode Island." since:1790 governor:@"Lincoln Chafee" sports:@"n/a" crime:@"n/a" themepark:@"Atlantic Beach Park, Westerly\nWater Wizz, Westerly" abbreviation:@"RI" museums:@"Artillery Company of Newport Military Museum (Newport)\nThe Jamestown Fire Department Memorial Museum (Jamestown)\nThe Museum of Natural History & Cormack Planetarium (Providence)\nNational Museum of American Illustration (Newport)\nThe New England Wireless & Steam Museum (East Greenwich)\nNewport Art Museum (Newport)\nProvidence Children's Museum (Providence)\nThe Rhode Island School of Design Museum of Art (Providence)\nSouth County Museum (Narragansett)" shoppingcenters:@"	Providence Place (Providence)\nRhode Island Mall (Warwick)\nWarwick Mall (Warwick)\nWestminster Arcade (Providence)" touristattractions:@"Block Island, Newport Cliff Walk, The Breakers, WaterFire, Rough Point, Providence Athenaeum, The Elms, Blitheworld Mansion & Gardens, Roger Williams Park Zoo" managedObjectContext:context];
    
    [State createStateWithName:@"South Carolina" population:4774839 statenickname:@"Palmetto State" history:@"The colony of Carolina was settled by wealthy nobles, mostly from Barbados. King Charles gave eight aristocrats a royal charter to settle Carolina (Carolina is Latin for \"Charles land\") because earlier they had helped him regain his throne.  The current United States Constitution was proposed for adoption by the States on September 17, 1787, and South Carolina was the 8th state to ratify it, on May 23, 1788.\nOn December 20, 1860, when it became clear that Abraham Lincoln would be the next president, South Carolina became the first state to declare its secession from the Union. On April 12, 1861, Confederate batteries began shelling Fort Sumter in Charleston Harbor, and the American Civil War began.\nEarly in the 20th century, South Carolina developed a thriving textile industry. The state also converted its agricultural base from cotton to more profitable crops, attracted large military bases, and created tourism industries. As the 21st century progresses, South Carolina attracts new business by having a 5% corporate income tax rate, no state property tax, no local income tax, no inventory tax, no sales tax on manufacturing equipment, industrial power or materials for finished products, no wholesale tax, no unitary tax on worldwide profits.\nOf extended controversy has been the state's display of the flags of the Confederate States of America, which was raised on the state capitol in 1962. The state capitol is located directly next to the University of South Carolina campus, so the move was seen as a protest against the court-ordered desegregation of the schools. A lawsuit calling for the flag to be removed was filed in 1994.On July 1, 2000, South Carolina became the last state to remove the Confederate flag, placed there in 1962, during Democratic Governor Fritz Hollings' term in office, from over its statehouse.\nThe flag by the monument continues to fuel controversy. The NAACP maintains an economic boycott of the state of South Carolina. The NCAA refuses to allow South Carolina to host NCAA athletic events whose locations are determined in advance.\nIn 2014, South Carolina was rated America's worst and poorest for its widespread, unclean, littered public properties, in the American State Litter Scorecard, presented at the American Society for Public Administration conference in Washington, DC." since:1788 governor:@"Nikki Haley" sports:@"n/a" crime:@"Myrtle Beach, Spartanburg, & Sumter" themepark:@"Family Kingdom Amusement Park, Myrtle Beach" abbreviation:@"SC" museums:@"Berkeley Museum (Monks Corner)\nThe Camden & Kershaw County Archives & Museum (Camden)\nThe Charleston Museum (Charleston)\nThe Columbia Museum of Art (Columbia)\nGibbes Museum of Art (Charleston)\nThe McKissick Museum (Columbia)\nThe Museum of York County (Rock Hill)\nThe South Carolina Railroad Museum (Winnsboro)\nThe South Carolina State Museum (Columbia)" shoppingcenters:@"Anderson Mall (Anderson)\nCitadel Mall (Charleston)\nCoastal Grand Mall (Myrtle Beach)\nColumbia Place (Columbia)\nColumbiana Centre (Columbia)\nDutch Square (Columbia)\nHaywood Mall (Greenville)\nInlet Square Mall (Murrells Inlet)\nMagnolia Mall (Florence)\nMagnolia Park Town Center (Greenville)\nThe Mall at Shelter Cove (Hilton Head Island)\nMyrtle Beach Mall (Myrtle Beach)\nNorthwoods Mall (North Charleston)\nPrince of Orange Mall (Orangeburg)\nRichland Mall (Columbia)\nRock Hill Galleria (Rock Hill)\nThe Village at Sandhill (Columbia)\nWestgate Mall (Spartanburg)" touristattractions:@"Historic Charleston, Myrtle Beach, Carolina Opry, BrookGreen Gardens, Riverbanks Zoo & Garden, USS Yorktown, Magnolia Plantation, Kiawah Island" managedObjectContext:context];
    
    [State createStateWithName:@"South Dakota" population:844877 statenickname:@"The Mount Rushmore State" history:@"Humans have lived in what is today South Dakota for at least several thousand years.\nBy 1500, the Arikara (or Ree) had settled in much of the Missouri River valley. European contact with the area began in 1743, when the LaVerendrye brothers explored the region. By the early 19th century, the Sioux had largely replaced the Arikara as the dominant group in the area.\nIn 1817, an American fur trading post was set up at present-day Fort Pierre, beginning continuous American settlement of the area.  Settlement by Americans and Europeans was by this time increasing rapidly, and in 1858 the Yankton Sioux signed the 1858 Treaty, ceding most of present-day eastern South Dakota to the United States. In 1861, the Dakota Territory was established by the United States government (this initially included North Dakota, South Dakota, and parts of Montana and Wyoming).\nA growing population caused Dakota Territory to be divided in half and President Benjamin Harrison signed proclamations formally admitting both South Dakota and North Dakota to the union on November 2, 1889. Harrison had the papers shuffled to obscure which one was signed first and the order went unrecorded.\nOn December 29, 1890, the Wounded Knee Massacre occurred on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation. Commonly cited as the last major armed conflict between the United States and the Lakota Sioux Nation, the massacre resulted in the deaths of at least 146 Sioux, many of them women and children.\nIn recent decades, South Dakota has been transformed from a state dominated by agriculture to one with a more diversified economy. The tourism industry has grown considerably since the completion of the interstate system in the 1960s, with the Black Hills becoming more important as a destination. The financial service industry began to grow in the state as well, with Citibank moving its credit card operations from New York to Sioux Falls in 1981, a move that has since been followed by several other financial companies. " since:1889 governor:@"Dennis Daugaard" sports:@"n/a" crime:@"n/a" themepark:@"Evan's Plunge, Hot Springs\nFlags & Wheels Indoor Racing, Rapid City\nStorybook Island, Rapid City\nThunder Road Family Fun Park, Aberdeen\nWild Water West, Sioux Falls" abbreviation:@"SD" museums:@"Grand River Museum (Lemmon)\nMammoth Site Museum (Hot Springs)\nNational Music Museum (Vermillion)\nPetrified Wood Park and Museum (Lemmon)\nThe South Dakota Hall of Fame (Chamberlain)" shoppingcenters:@"Empire Mall (Sioux Falls)\nRushmore Mall (Rapid City)" touristattractions:@"Crazy Horse Memorial, Mitchell Corn Palace, Black Hills, Wall Drug, Sioux Falls Park, Spearfish Canyon" managedObjectContext:context];
    
    [State createStateWithName:@"Tennessee" population:6495978 statenickname:@"Volunteer State" history:@"The first recorded European excursions into what is now called Tennessee were three expeditions led by Spanish explorers, namely Hernando de Soto in 1540, Tristan de Luna in 1559, and Juan Pardo in 1567. Pardo recorded the name \"Tanasqui\" from a local Indian village, which evolved to the state's current name.  The first British settlement in what is now Tennessee was built in 1756 by settlers from the colony of South Carolina at Fort Loudoun, near present-day Vonore.  Tennessee was admitted to the Union on June 1, 1796 as the 16th state.  In February 1861, secessionists in Tennessee's state government—led by Governor Isham Harris—sought voter approval for a convention to sever ties with the United States, but Tennessee voters rejected the referendum by a 54–46% margin. The strongest opposition to secession came from East Tennessee (which later tried to form a separate Union-aligned state).  Many major battles of the American Civil War were fought in Tennessee—most of them Union victories. Ulysses S. Grant and the U.S. Navy captured control of the Cumberland and Tennessee rivers in February 1862. They held off the Confederate counterattack at Shiloh in April. Memphis fell to the Union in June, following a naval battle on the Mississippi River in front of the city. The Capture of Memphis and Nashville gave the Union control of the western and middle sections; this control was confirmed at the Battle of Murfreesboro in early January 1863 and by the subsequent Tullahoma Campaign." since:1796 governor:@"Bill Haslam" sports:@"Memphis Grizzlies (Memphis, NBA), Nashville Predators (Nashville, NHL), Tennessee Titans (Nashville, NFL)" crime:@"Knoxville, Nashville, Jackson, & Memphis" themepark:@"Dollywood, Pigeon Forge\nLake Winnipasokah, East Ridge\nNASCAR Speedpark, Sevierville\nOber Gatlinburg, Gatlinburg" abbreviation:@"TN" museums:@"The Abraham Lincoln Library and Museum Lincoln (Harrogate)\nAmerican Museum of Science and Energy (Oak Ridge)\nCarroll Reece Museum (Johnson City)\nCheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art (Nashville)\nCountry Music Hall of Fame and Museum (Nashville)\nGrand Ole Opry House & Opry Museum (Nashville)\nHistoric Mt. Pleasant/Maury Phosphate Museum (Mount Pleasant)\nThe Houston Museum of Decorative Arts (Chattanooga)\nKnoxville Museum of Art (Knoxville)\nMuseum of the Tennessee School for the Deaf (Knoxville)\nThe National Knife Museum (Chattanooga)\nThe National Medal of Honor Museum of Military History (Chattanooga)\nTennessee State Museum (Nashville)\nPink Palace Family of Museums (Memphis)\nThe Tennessee Valley Railroad Museum (Chattanooga)" shoppingcenters:@"Avenue Carriage Crossing (Collierville)\nBradley Square Mall (Cleveland)\nCollege Square Mall (Morristown)\nCoolSprings Galleria (Franklin)\nFoothills Mall (Maryville)\nGovernor's Square Mall (Clarksville)\nHamilton Place (Chattanooga)\nHickory Hollow Mall (Antioch)\nHickory Ridge Mall (Memphis)\nIndian Lake Village (Hendersonville)\nKingsport Town Center (Kingsport)\nKnoxville Center (Knoxville)\nMall at Green Hills (Nashville)\nMall at Johnson City (Johnson City)\nNorthgate Mall (Hixson)\nOak Court Mall (Memphis)\nOak Ridge City Center (Oak Ridge)\nOpry Mills (Nashville)\nPeabody Place (Memphis)\nRaleigh Springs Mall (Memphis)\nRivergate Mall (Nashville)\nShops of Saddle Creek (Germantown)\nSouthland Mall (Memphis)\nStones River Mall (Murfreesboro)\nThe Avenue Murfreesboro (Murfreesboro)\nWest Town Mall (Knoxville)\nWolfchase Galleria (Memphis)" touristattractions:@"Elvis Presley’s Graceland, Tennessee Aquarium, Chattanooga, Memphis Zoo & Aquarium, Downtown Nashville, Ruby Falls" managedObjectContext:context];
    
    [State createStateWithName:@"Texas" population:26448193 statenickname:@"Lone Star State" history:@"No culture was dominant in the present-day Texas region, and many peoples inhabited the area.Native American tribes that lived inside the boundaries of present-day Texas include the Alabama, Apache, Atakapan, Bidai, Caddo, Coahuiltecan, Comanche, Choctaw, Coushatta, Hasinai, Jumano, Karankawa, Kickapoo, Kiowa, Tonkawa, and Wichita. The name Texas derives from táyshaʔ, a word in the Caddoan language of the Hasinai, which means \"friends\" or \"allies\".\nThe first historical document related to Texas was a map of the Gulf Coast, created in 1519 by Spanish explorer Alonso Álvarez de Pineda. When France began settling Louisiana, mostly in the southern part of the state, in 1716 Spanish authorities responded by founding a new series of missions in East Texas.Two years later, they created San Antonio as the first Spanish civilian settlement in the area.\nWithin Mexico, tensions continued between federalists and centralists. In early 1835, wary Texians formed Committees of Correspondence and Safety. The unrest erupted into armed conflict in late 1835 at the Battle of Gonzales.This launched the Texas Revolution, and over the next two months, the Texians defeated all Mexican troops in the region. The newly elected Texian delegates to the Convention of 1836 quickly signed a Declaration of Independence on March 2, forming the Republic of Texas. As early as 1837, the Republic made several attempts to negotiate annexation with the United States. Opposition within the republic from the nationalist faction, along with strong abolitionist opposition within the United States, slowed Texas's admission into the Union. Texas was finally annexed when the expansionist James K. Polk won the election of 1844.\nAfter a series of United States victories, the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo ended the two-year war. In return, for US$18,250,000, Mexico gave the U.S. undisputed control of Texas, ceded the Mexican Cession in 1848, most of which today is called the American Southwest, and Texas's borders were established at the Rio Grande. In 1900, Texas received the deadliest natural disaster in U.S. history during the Galveston hurricane. On January 10, 1901, the first major oil well in Texas, Spindletop, was found south of Beaumont. Other fields were later discovered nearby in East Texas, West Texas, and under the Gulf of Mexico. The resulting \"Oil Boom\" transformed Texas. Oil production eventually averaged three million barrels per day at its peak in 1972.\nTexas modernized and expanded its system of higher education through the 1960s. The state created a comprehensive plan for higher education, funded in large part by oil revenues, and a central state apparatus designed to manage state institutions more efficiently. These changes helped Texas universities receive federal research funds.\nOn November 22, 1963, President John F. Kennedy was assassinated in Dallas." since:1845 governor:@"Rick Perry" sports:@"FC Dallas (Frisco, MLS), Dallas Cowboys (Arlington, NFL), Dallas Mavericks (Dallas, NBA), Dallas Stars (Dallas, NHL), Houston Astros (Houston, MLB), Houston Dynamo (Houston, MLS), Houston Rockets (Houston NBA), Houston Texans (Houston, NFL), San Antonio Spurs (San Antonio, NBA), Texas Rangers (Arlington, MLB)" crime:@"Houston, Beaumont, Texarkana, Odessa, & Weslaco" themepark:@"	Adventure Kingdom, Lumberton\nAquatica, San Antonio\nGalveston Island Historic Pleasure Pier, Galveston\nGrand Texas Theme Park, New Caney\nJoyland Amusement Park, Lubbock\nKemah Boardwalk, Kemah\nMorgan's Wonderland, San Antonio\nNRH2O, North Richland Hills\nSandy Lake Amusement Park, Carrollton\nSchlitterbahn, New Braunfels\nSchlitterbahn Beach, South Padre Island\nSchlitterbahn Galveston Island, Galveston\nSeaWorld San Antonio, San Antonio\nSplashtown San Antonio, San Antonio\nSix Flags Fiesta Texas, San Antonio\nSix Flags Hurricane Harbor, Arlington\nSix Flags Over Texas, Arlington\nWet'n'Wild SplashTown, Spring\nWonderland Park, Amarillo\nZDT'S Amusement Center, Seguin" abbreviation:@"TX" museums:@"The Age of Steam Railway Museum (Dallas)\nAmerican Airpower Heritage Museum (Midland)\nThe American Quarter Horse Heritage Center & Museum (Amarillo)\nThe Amon Carter Museum (Fort Worth)\nAustin Museum of Art (Austin)\nThe Brazoria County Historical Museum (Angleton)\nThe Buckhorn Saloon & Museum (San Antonio)\nThe Cavanaugh Flight Museum (Addison)\nThe Centennial Museum (El Paso)\nThe Chappell Hill Historical Society Museum (Chappell Hill)\nThe Contempory Arts Museum (Houston)\nDallas Museum of Art (Dallas)\nEl Paso Museum of Art (El Paso)\nThe Fort Worth Museum of Science and History (Fort Worth)\nThe Heard Natural Science Museum and Wildlife Sanctuary (McKinney)\nThe Houston Holocaust Museum (Houston)\nThe Houston Museum of Natural Science (Houston)\nInternational Museum of Cultures (Dallas)\nKimbell Art Museum (Fort Worth)\nLongview Museum of Fine Arts (Longview)\nMcAllen International Museum (McAlle\nThe Marion Koogler McNay Art Museum (San Antonio)\nThe Meadows Museum (Dallas)\nThe Menil Collection Museum (Houston)\nThe Modern Art Museum (Calquier)\nThe Modern Art Museum (Fort Worth)\nThe Museum of Fine Arts (Houston)\nMuseum of the American Windmill (Lubbock)\n Museum of the Big Bend (Alpine)\nThe Museum of Health and Medical Science (Houston)\nMuseum of the Southwest (Midland)\nThe Museum of Texas Tech University (Lubbock)\nNational Museum of Funeral History (Houston)\nNational Scouting Museum (Irving)\nThe Panhandle-Plains Historical Museum (Canyon)\nThe Petroleum Museum (Midland)\nThe Red River Valley Museum (Vernon)\nSan Antonio Museum of Art (San Antonio)\nSam Houston Memorial Museum (Huntsville)\nThe Stephenville Museum (Stephenville)\nThe Strecker Museum Complex (Waco)\nThe Texas Air Museum (Rio Hondo)\nThe Texas Energy Museum (Beaumont)\nTexas Forestry Museum (Lufkin)\nThe Texas Memorial Museum (Austin)\nTexas Military Force